  "prompt": "How did the saying, \"goodnight Vienna\" originate?",
  "response": "The saying \"goodnight Vienna\" is believed to have originated in the world of entertainment, particularly in the context of music hall and vaudeville acts in the early to mid-20th century. The phrase suggests the end of a performance or a situation, similar to saying \"that's all folks!\" \n\nThe phrase may have become more widely known through its usage in popular culture or media. One of the notable references comes from the 1970s British television series \"The Goodies,\" in which it was used humorously. The exact origins of the phrase can be somewhat unclear, but it is thought to reflect a sentiment of finality or concluding an affair, possibly drawing on the notion of Vienna as a place associated with cultural richness and musical heritage.\n\nAs with many idiomatic expressions, its usage and specific connotations can evolve over time, often expanding beyond its original context.",
